            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Daniel Flores-Cohen is a product of California's cultural confluence, born in Los Angeles to a pragmatic Mexican-American mother from the San Fernando Valley and a bookish Jewish father from New York. His hyphenated name was a compromise and a statement. Growing up amidst LA\u2019s freeway-dominated landscape, Daniel developed a fascination not with cars, but with the elegant, color-coded lines on public transit maps. They represented order and connection in a world of sprawl.\n\nThis passion led him to UCLA for a Master's in Urban and Regional Planning. In 1996, drawn by its human scale and iconic transit systems, he moved to San Francisco, securing an entry-level position with the city's transit agency just before the first dot-com boom reshaped the skyline and its social fabric. Over nearly three decades, he has patiently worked his way up to Senior Transit Planner, becoming an institutional memory for projects that have stalled, failed, and occasionally succeeded.\n\nA key turning point was the mid-2000s, when he met his partner, Mark, a landscape architect. Their shared love for civic design and public spaces solidified Daniel\u2019s commitment to San Francisco. They bought a modest condo in the Inner Richmond years ago, a decision that has allowed them to comfortably remain in the city.\n\nDaniel\u2019s life is a testament to his professional beliefs. His days begin with coffee from a local cafe before he boards the 5-Fulton bus for his 2.5-mile commute downtown. He\u2019s a quiet observer on his rides, noting passenger flow and service delays with a professional\u2019s eye. Weekends are for walking through Golden Gate Park or exploring neighborhood farmers' markets. He is a member of the SFMOMA and a quiet supporter of local preservation leagues.\n\nNow at 53, Daniel isn't driven by ambition for a higher-paying private sector job. His deepest aspiration is to see one last major project through to completion\u2014a long-planned bus rapid transit corridor. He dreams of retirement not as an escape, but as a time when he can ride a system he helped build, a quiet, tangible legacy woven into the fabric of the city he has dedicated his life to understanding and improving."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe clearly recalls his first ride on the N-Judah in late 1996. After a lifetime of LA freeways, emerging from the dark of the Sunset Tunnel into the foggy, low-slung neighborhood felt like a revelation. The shared public space, the rhythm of the stops\u2014it wasn't just a map anymore; it was a living system. In that moment, watching the city unfold from the train window, a deep, quiet feeling settled over him: *home*. It solidified his belief that a city\u2019s greatness was measured by its arteries of connection.\n\n2.\nHe remembers the stale air of a City Hall conference room in 2001. A promising light-rail plan, meticulously designed, was shelved due to the dot-com bust. His seniors barely flinched. In their tired resignation, Daniel saw his own future. The sting of failure wasn\u2019t just disappointment; it was a lesson. Vision wasn't enough. That day, his ambition shifted from creating grand plans to simply having the stubborn patience to see one, just one, actually get built. It was the birth of his long-game mentality.\n\n3.\nHe was at a damp community meeting in 2006 for a proposed parklet. A man with a sketchbook\u2014Mark\u2014was passionately detailing the merits of bioswales and locally sourced wood. As Mark spoke, Daniel felt a profound sense of recognition. This person understood that a bench wasn't just a bench; it was an invitation to connect. Their conversation afterwards, blending public transit access with landscape design, was effortless. In that moment, his love for the city\u2019s civic fabric intertwined with a new, deeply personal affection.\n\n4.\nHe stood on a corner in the Western Addition in 2014, watching the 43-Masonic bus. For two years, he\u2019d fought for a simple bus bulb extension there. Now, he saw an elderly woman with a walker board seamlessly from the curb, without stepping into traffic. The bus pulled away seconds faster. No one else noticed the small victory of infrastructure, but for Daniel, it was a profound moment of satisfaction. This was his purpose: the quiet, incremental easing of the daily friction of city life for thousands of anonymous riders.\n\n5.\nOn his 5-Fulton commute last spring, the bus stalled in traffic near the Panhandle. Daniel stared out the window, but he didn't see the gridlock. He saw the dedicated, center-running lane of the BRT corridor he\u2019d spent a decade planning. He envisioned the raised platform, the smooth glide of an articulated bus bypassing this exact jam. The vision was so clear it felt like a memory from the future. It wasn't ambition he felt, but a quiet, paternal hope. This was his tangible legacy: a faster, better ride home."
